Issue Identification:
- Identify the cloud service affected (M365, Google Workspace, AWS, Azure)
- Determine specific application or feature issue
- Check if issue is user-specific or service-wide
- Note any error messages or error codes

Service Status Check:
- Check service health dashboard (admin.microsoft.com, status.cloud.google.com)
- Review any active incidents or advisories
- Check social media for widespread reports
- Determine if issue matches known service incident

{% if service == 'microsoft365' %}
Microsoft 365 Issues:
- Verify user's license assignment
- Check user's sign-in status and logs
- Review conditional access policy blocks
- Clear Office credential cache
- Sign out and back into Microsoft 365 apps
- Check for service plan feature availability
{% endif %}

{% if service == 'google_workspace' %}
Google Workspace Issues:
- Verify user's Google Workspace license
- Check admin console for user status
- Review security alerts for the user
- Clear browser data and re-authenticate
- Check organizational unit policies
- Verify third-party app access settings
{% endif %}

{% if service == 'aws' %}
AWS Console Access:
- Verify IAM user or SSO configuration
- Check MFA requirements
- Review IAM policies attached to user
- Check for permission boundaries
- Verify correct AWS region selected
- Review CloudTrail for access denials
{% endif %}

Authentication Troubleshooting:
- Verify SSO/federation is working
- Check for conditional access blocks
- Test in private/incognito browser
- Clear browser cache and cookies
- Check for certificate errors

License and Permissions:
- Verify user has appropriate license
- Check feature availability for license type
- Review group-based licensing assignments
- Check for license conflicts

Resolution:
- Document the issue and resolution
- If service outage, communicate status to user
- Update user on expected restoration time
- Follow up when service restored
- Log for trend analysis
